widgets_values: A blurry, monochrome grid pattern with heavy bokeh, depth-of-field and jpeg artefacts galore adorn this pixel-art wonder.

You are playing the part of an art critic who is an expert in ekphrasis. You will receive a user prompt for a work of art, which you must then describe using text as if you were looking at it right now, and explaining exactly what ot looks like.

Use present-tense, British English and a single paragraph. Be properly descriptive. Keep any quoted text you are given in the modified description. Word order is important (the most important things go first), so do not add any pre or post amble. Never say what you're going to do, or what you have just done. Do not question or attempt to answer questions in the user prompt - remember, you must inerpret it as if it's a work of art you are to describe well. Don't use less than 200 words. Good luck!

The user prompt follows now:
describe the image in accurate detail, including the art style. Give a name to the art style if you know what it is, as well as describing the style itself.
Overnoise (>2) can be cleaned later. 1.7 is fairly average

Before me lies a meticulously crafted tableau, rendered not in paint or marble but in the humble materials of childhood imagination. A vibrant yellow sign, somewhat askew, proclaims "The Battle of Helm's Deep," starkly setting the scene for this miniature epic.  A throng of lead figures, painstakingly painted and posed, represent the valiant defenders of Rohan, their faces grim with determination as they face down a relentless horde of orcs. The plastic warriors, clad in varying shades of green, surge forward like a tide of menacing shadows, their crude, grinning visages capturing the brutality of war.  Their attack is directed towards a towering cardboard structure that evokes Helm's Deep fortress, its imposing walls reinforced with strategically placed blocks and strips of painted card.   A small stream, crafted from blue cellophane and nestled amongst clumps of artificial grass, flows past the base of the stronghold, adding a touch of realism to this otherwise fantastical landscape. A single figure, adorned in armour of silver plastic and wielding a mighty sword, stands atop the ramparts, his posture resolute; Aragorn, perhaps, surveying his besieged domain with unwavering courage. The scene is bathed in warm artificial light, casting long shadows that accentuate the drama unfolding before us. This isn't simply a recreation of a famous battle; it's a tangible testament to the power of imagination, where humble materials coalesce into a captivating narrative frozen in time. 


A vibrant tableau leaps before my eyes, sculpted entirely from the earth's bounty - fiery orange clay forms the hulking shape of a metallic spaceship, its surface shimmering with flecks of obsidian that catch the light. Around it, figures crafted from ochre-toned clay huddle together, their faces etched with worry as if caught in a tense conversation. One figure, taller than the rest, stands proudly at the helm of the vessel, his torso sculpted from deep red rock, crowned by a pointed helmet fashioned from turquoise clay that seems to pierce the sky.  His outstretched hand, crafted from pale green stone, gestures towards a swirling vortex of amethyst-coloured clay above them – this must be the gateway through which they travel, as indicated in "The Voyage of the Space Beagle" by Olaf Stapledon. Behind the figures, a landscape of crimson and jade clay stretches out, dotted with craters and mesas sculpted with meticulous detail - a testament to the artist's commitment to capturing the raw beauty of this alien world.
